05432nam a22009855i 9780691214221DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20202003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912142217 a10.1515/97806912142212doi  a(DE-B1597)554820  a(OCoLC)1191864050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD9915.I83bY36 2002eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a338.4/7677390945232231 aYanagisako, Sylvia Junko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProducing Culture and Capital :bFamily Firms in Italy /cSylvia Junko Yanagisako. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b1 map. 5 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChapter One. PRODUCING CULTURE AND CAPITAL -- tChapter Two. THE GENERATION OF FIRMS -- tChapter Three. PATRIARCHAL DESIRE -- tChapter Four. BETRAYAL AS A FORCE OF PRODUCTION -- tChapter Five. CAPITAL AND GENDERED SENTIMENTS -- tChapter Six. CONCLUSION -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProducing Culture and Capital is a major theoretical contribution to the anthropological literature on capitalism, as well as a rich case study of kinship and gender relations in northern Italy. Drawing on ethnographic and archival research on thirty-eight firms in northern Italy's silk industry, Sylvia Yanagisako illuminates the cultural processes through which sentiments, desires, and commitments motivate and shape capitalist family firms. She shows how flexible specialization is produced through the cultural dynamics of capital accumulation, management succession, firm expansion and diversification, and the reproduction and division of firms. In doing so, Yanagisako addresses two gaps in Marx's and Weber's theories of capitalism: the absence of an adequate cultural theory of capitalist motivation and the absence of attention to kinship and gender. By demonstrating that kinship and gender are crucial in structuring capitalist action, this study reveals these two gaps to be different facets of the same omission. A process-oriented approach to class formation and class subjectivity enables the author to incorporate the material and ideological struggles within families into an analysis of class-making and self-making. Yanagisako concludes that both "provincial" and "global" capitalist orientations and strategies operate in an industry that has always been integrated into regional and international relations of production and distribution. Her approach to culture and capitalism as mutually constituted processes offers an alternative to both universal models of capitalism as a mode of production and essentialist models of distinctive "cultures of capitalism."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aFamily-owned business enterpriseszItalyzComo. 0aSilk industryzItalyzComo. 4aAbercrombie, Nicholas. 4aAsian capitalism. 4aBarbieri firm. 4aBarbieri, Mario. 4aBlim, Michael. 4aCasati firm. 4aCasati, Pietro. 4aDelaney, Carol. 4aGalbusera firm. 4aGalbusera, Antonio. 4aHirschman, Albert O. 4aMartinelli firm. 4aMartinelli, Alberto. 4aPedretti firm. 4aPiore, Michael J. 4aRandazzo firm. 4aSabel, Charles F. 4aScotti, Franco. 4aStamperia Breva firm. 4aVenturini, Piercarlo. 4aWeber, Max. 4aemotion. 4afamily histories. 4afather-son succession. 4alabor. 4asubcontracting firms. 4avertical integration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978